  "research_html": "<div class=\"research-section\">\n<p class=\"research-text\">Euclid&#x27;s <strong>Elements</strong> is a foundational mathematical treatise composed in Greek around 300 BCE. Organized into thirteen books, it systematically compiles the geometry and number theory of its time into a coherent logical structure built from definitions, postulates, and common notions or axioms. The work begins with plane geometry, establishing fundamental results such as the properties of triangles, parallels, and areas, including the Pythagorean theorem. It then progresses to number theory, presenting concepts like divisibility, prime numbers, and the Euclidean algorithm for finding the greatest common divisor. The final books address solid geometry, culminating in the construction and proof that only five regular polyhedra—the Platonic solids—can exist. Its primary purpose was pedagogical, aiming to instruct students in mathematics through a rigorous sequence of deductive proofs.</p>\n<p class=\"research-text\">The text survives in its entirety, though no original manuscript exists. Modern scholarship relies on later Byzantine copies and a rich tradition of translations, first into Arabic during the Islamic Golden Age and later into Latin, which were crucial for its transmission to medieval Europe. It is believed to have been composed in Alexandria, synthesizing earlier Greek mathematical knowledge into a single, authoritative compilation. The <strong>Elements</strong> is arguably the most influential textbook ever written, serving as the standard for teaching geometry, logic, and the axiomatic method for over two millennia and profoundly shaping the development of scientific and philosophical thought.</p>\n</div>",
